00:02:33.390 --> 00:02:34.870
That's the nice thing.

00:02:34.870 --> 00:02:38.680
So I would like to know the
null space of that matrix.

00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:44.980
I'd like to solve so the
null space, N of A-- I'm

00:02:44.980 --> 00:02:50.200
solving Av equals all 0s.

00:02:50.200 --> 00:02:53.130
So some combination
of those three columns

00:02:53.130 --> 00:02:54.720
will give me the 0 column.

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:58.830
Let me write it
in as a 0 column.

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:00.920
What could v be?

00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:04.380
What combination of that column,
that column, and that column

00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:06.040
give 0, 0?

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:09.320
Now, I know there are some
interesting combinations

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:14.750
because I-- only amounts to two
equations with three unknowns,

00:03:14.750 --> 00:03:16.620
v1, v2, v3.

00:03:16.620 --> 00:03:21.860
I want to multiply that by
v1, that by v2, that by v3.

00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:25.200
So I have three unknowns,
but I've only two 0s

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:27.390
to get, only two equations.

00:03:27.390 --> 00:03:29.470
And if I have three
unknowns and two equations,

00:03:29.470 --> 00:03:31.700
there will be lots of solutions.

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:33.330
And I can see one.

00:03:33.330 --> 00:03:39.710
Do you see that if I add
that and that, I get 4, 10

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:44.090
And that's the same-- 4, 10
